{"id":"2303.00411","submitter":"Katharina Klioba","authors":"Katharina Klioba and Mark Veraar","title":"Pathwise Uniform Convergence of Time Discretisation Schemes for SPDEs","comments":"45 pages, added Sections 6.3, 7.3 on pathwise uniform error estimates\n  on the full time interval","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.NA cs.NA math.AP math.FA math.PR","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/","abstract":"  In this paper we prove convergence rates for time discretisation schemes for\nsemi-linear stochastic evolution equations with additive or multiplicative\nGaussian noise, where the leading operator $A$ is the generator of a strongly\ncontinuous semigroup $S$ on a Hilbert space $X$, and the focus is on\nnon-parabolic problems. The main results are optimal bounds for the uniform\nstrong error $$\\mathrm{E}_{k}^{\\infty} := \\Big(\\mathbb{E} \\sup_{j\\in \\{0,\n\\ldots, N_k\\}} \\|U(t_j) - U^j\\|^p\\Big)^{1/p},$$ where $p \\in [2,\\infty)$, $U$\nis the mild solution, $U^j$ is obtained from a time discretisation scheme, $k$\nis the step size, and $N_k = T/k$. The usual schemes such as\nsplitting/exponential Euler, implicit Euler, and Crank-Nicolson, etc.\\ are\nincluded as special cases. Under conditions on the nonlinearity and the noise\nwe show\n  - $\\mathrm{E}_{k}^{\\infty}\\lesssim k \\log(T/k)$ (linear equation, additive\nnoise, general $S$);\n  - $\\mathrm{E}_{k}^{\\infty}\\lesssim \\sqrt{k} \\log(T/k)$ (nonlinear equation,\nmultiplicative noise, contractive $S$);\n  - $\\mathrm{E}_{k}^{\\infty}\\lesssim k \\log(T/k)$ (nonlinear wave equation,\nmultiplicative noise).\n  The logarithmic factor can be removed if the splitting scheme is used with a\n(quasi)-contractive $S$. The obtained bounds coincide with the optimal bounds\nfor SDEs. Most of the existing literature is concerned with bounds for the\nsimpler pointwise strong error $$\\mathrm{E}_k:=\\bigg(\\sup_{j\\in\n\\{0,\\ldots,N_k\\}}\\mathbb{E} \\|U(t_j) - U^{j}\\|^p\\bigg)^{1/p}.$$ Applications to\nMaxwell equations, Schr\\\"odinger equations, and wave equations are included.\nFor these equations our results improve and reprove several existing results\nwith a unified method.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 1 Mar 2023 11:07:30 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Fri, 17 Mar 2023 16:36:26 GMT"}],"update_date":"2023-03-20"}
